occurrenceRemarks: I found this pyro with Hunter Meakin and Brian Nielsen as we walked back to camp. This young adult male snake was active and on the crawl at 4:09pm in the afternoon, 73F, partly cloudy/sunny with a few small showers of rain in the region in the previous few days. It was a thin but healthy young adult snake. The animal was found moving away from us slowly under some sagebrush that I was about to walk right past. This pyro was found within its known range, but I'm keenly interested in the other canyons within the range and the 2 other out-of-range mountain ranges to the north. I've been driving out here from Seattle for the last 4 years hoping to find a pyro and this animal was my first pyro ever! \o/ https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gBN6GXj1CUg Thanks to Bryan Hamilton, Alan St.John, Mark Hazel, Jimi Gragg, my trip companions Hunter Meakin/Brian Nielsen, and anybody else targetting snakes for science around the edges of their known ranges.

occurrenceRemarks: The previous week had nightly lows as cool as 24F which gradually rose into the low 50’s making for an excellent week of finding reptiles in West Utah/Eastern NV. Daily high was around 76 but there were a few cycles of a burst of rain followed by sun through the afternoon. Our snake surveying team had all hiked very hard all week, with the clock running down everyone went to bed. It was the last night with the group and no lampropeltis had been found. I went out for one last stroll and like a fevered dream found myself standing in front of a pyro crossing a road wondering if it was real. Temp gun said 50-55F when taking surface readings. My car was 66F ambient but likely still a bit warm from a 2.5 hour drive earlier in the day. It was 9:04pm, dark night in the canyon when it was somewhat light an hour earlier. This pyro was found within its known range in one of the same canyons visited last year where another pyro was found. Thanks to Bryan Hamilton, Alan St.John, Mark Hazel, Hunter Meakin, Amanda Cook, and Susan Myers, and anybody else targetting snakes for science around the edges of their known ranges.

occurrenceRemarks: What a snake <3 It had rained pretty hard a few hours earlier and was still cloudy. Air temps in the low 70s. Found a little ways off the trail. It was dark and cloudy so the pictures aren't as great as they could have been. Female, no eggs (probably laid a couple of weeks ago, if she had any).

occurrenceRemarks: Cruised by Miles going up a canyon away from water at exactly 60° right before sunset. A species I’ve dreamt of seeing for years, and my main target in Utah in 2024. Truly a buzzer beater, with my last day herping in the state this year! Such a fantastic find, a snake I won’t forget any time soon, and one of my favorites of 2024 Millard County
